{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508711"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11352"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11352"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.41,0.3,0.15,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3997"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52441"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"3997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/3997"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37794"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1362"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42576"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52441"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of weight gain, facial rounding, and easy bruising. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears cushingoid with central obesity, facial plethora, and thin skin with multiple bruises. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Investigations reveal elevated 24-hour urinary free cortisol on three separate occasions. A low-dose dexamethasone suppression test shows a plasma cortisol level of 80 nmol/L (normal \u0026lt;50 nmol/L).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI of the pituitary gland","High-dose dexamethasone suppression test","Morning plasma ACTH level","CT scan of the adrenal glands","Corticotropin-releasing hormone test"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features and biochemical evidence consistent with Cushing\u0027s syndrome. The next step in management is to determine the cause of the hypercortisolism. \u003Cstrong\u003EMorning plasma ACTH level\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it helps differentiate between ACTH-dependent and ACTH-independent causes of Cushing\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the ACTH level is normal or elevated, it suggests an ACTH-dependent cause (such as a pituitary adenoma or ectopic ACTH-secreting tumour). If the ACTH level is suppressed, it indicates an ACTH-independent cause (such as an adrenal tumour).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the pituitary gland\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if the ACTH level is elevated, suggesting a pituitary source of ACTH. However, it is premature to perform this test before determining ACTH dependence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-dose dexamethasone suppression test\u003C/strong\u003E can help differentiate between pituitary and ectopic sources of ACTH in ACTH-dependent Cushing\u0027s syndrome. However, this test is not the next step as ACTH dependence has not yet been established.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the adrenal glands\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if the ACTH level is suppressed, suggesting an adrenal source of cortisol. However, like the MRI, it is premature to perform this test before determining ACTH dependence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorticotropin-releasing hormone test\u003C/strong\u003E can also help differentiate between pituitary and ectopic sources of ACTH in ACTH-dependent Cushing\u0027s syndrome. However, like the high-dose dexamethasone suppression test, it is not the next step as ACTH dependence has not yet been established.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the morning plasma ACTH level is the most appropriate next step as it guides further investigation and helps localise the source of hypercortisolism in Cushing\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Once Cushing\u0027s syndrome is diagnosed, a serum ACTH level is the first step to localise the underlying pathology.","Biochemical diagnosis of Cushing\u0027s syndrome typically requires at least two cross-confirmatory results among commonly-used tests."],"references":["Nieman LK. Diagnosis of Cushing\u0027s Syndrome in the Modern Era. Endocrinol Metab Clin North Am. 2018 Jun;47(2):259-273. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29754631/","Nieman LK. Cushing\u0027s syndrome: update on signs, symptoms and biochemical screening. Eur J Endocrinol. 2015 Oct;173(4):M33-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26156970/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37794"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11352"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37794"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-05T11:50:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T22:59:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"d